Differences in shape and spinulation of the postabdomen and size of spines on antenna II could be explained in terms of functional morphology. Postabdomen, the main pushing organ of benthic (and some vegetation-living) taxa of the Anomopoda , is traditionally regarded as the main sourse of their diagnostic characters (
Smirnov 1996
;
Kotov 2009
;
Van Damme et al. 2011
;
Van Damme & Sinev 2013
). The spines on antenna II are also very characteristic for truly benthic animals (
Fryer 1968
;
Kotov 2006
), and their size has a great significance for the taxonomy of different groups of the Anomopoda .
